const storyGrammar = {
    "origin": ["#[subject:#noun#]story#"],
    "story": ["<p class='uppercase'>#subject# Piece</p><p>#verb# #subject#. #phrase1#. #phrase2#.</p>"],
    "phrase1": ["Hang it on the wall", "Listen until Dawn", "Throw it in the garbage", "Wash it thoroughly with soap", "Place a stone under it"],
    "phrase2": ["Invite everybody", "This should be done in the evening", "Do not tell anyone what you did", "Have absent thoughts for a long time", "Take a walk"],
    "noun": ["an empty bag", "the sky", "a scarred painting", "the smell of the moon", "a heart beat", "an orange"],
    "verb": ["Drill a hole in", "Make a recording of", "Listen to", "Draw", "Imagine"]
}


function main() {
    let grammar = tracery.createGrammar(storyGrammar);
    let story = grammar.flatten("#origin#");

    const storyDiv = document.createElement('div');
    storyDiv.style = "font-size: 30px; margin: 10%; line-height: 1.5; width: 480px;";
    storyDiv.innerHTML = story;

    document.body.insertAdjacentElement("beforeend", storyDiv);
}


setTimeout(main, 10);

description:
I continued working on yesterday's code because I was fascinated by how these visuals develop over time. As I was experimenting with it, I felt it could lend itself beautifully to some abstract pointillistic forms- that I love working on by hand. 

Also, while working on these I got a sense that noise somehow made the forms more organic- almost as if it was led by an inherent rhythm. What I have come to enjoy the most while working on these sketches is how little tweaks can completely change the visual output. These three sketches use the same code, with changes in the factor by which the variable x is being divided. 

