Day 8: As someone who loves making things by hand, I have had an interesting relationship with the process of making art digitally. On one hand, it makes it technically so much easier to add detail, yet it can be challenging to achieve the imperfection that makes handwork so endearing.

The random function in a way lets us do that. More than the final visual, it is the process that I find intriguing- the experimentation is super fun. Here are some that I tried today. (The random function sure does throw up surprises- Some of these color combinations are ones I would have never tried on my own)

The code is a modification of the grass example we did in class.  

//Code modified from the Grass example by Justin Bakse

function setup() {
	createCanvas(windowWidth, windowHeight);
	noLoop();
}

function draw() {
	background(200, 150, 15);

	noStroke();
	fill(random(220), random(220), random(220));
	stroke(random(220), random(180), random(60));
	strokeWeight(random(0, 2))
	drawFn(0, height * 0.5, width, random(40));
	fill(random(220), random(220), random(220));
	stroke(random(220), random(180), random(60));
	strokeWeight(random(0, 2))
	drawFn(200, height * 0.9 + 100, width, random(60));
}

function drawFn(left, top, width, height) {
	for (var x = left; x < left + width; x++) {
		var y = top + height * random(10);
		var c = random(0, 90);
		var d = (random(0, 50) * 0.5 + random(0, 50) * 0.5);
		ellipse(x + y, x - y, x + y, y + c);
		ellipse(x - y, x + y, x - y, x + d);
		ellipse(x + y, x - y, x + d, y + c);
		ellipse(x - y, x + y, y + c, x + d);
		line(x, y, x + d / 10, y + c / 10);
		line(x + y, x + y, x + d / 10, y + c / 10);
		line(x + d / 500, y + c / 500, x / 500, y / 500);
		line(x + d / 100, y + c / 100, x / 100, y / 100);
	}
}

